05829nam a22007095i 9780228009559DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280095597 a10.1515/97802280095592doi  a(DE-B1597)654631  a(OCoLC)1273203867  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aP306b.N446 2022 7aLAN0230002bisacsh04a418.0222300aNegotiating Linguistic Plurality :bTranslation and Multilingualism in Canada and Beyond /ced. by Şehnaz Tahir Gürçağlar, María Constanza Guzmán. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tTranslation as Epistemic Leverage over Multilingual Romani Borders -- tThe Matrix of Multilingual Memory: Binjamin Wilkomirski, Rigoberta Menchú, and the Power of Abject Atrocity -- tTranslating the Multilingual: Reflections on French Accounts of Eighteenth-Century India -- tTranslation Frequencies: Tuning In or Out in Multilingual Settings -- tTranslating (in) Caribbean Periodicals: Negotiating Multilingualism in Print Culture -- tMultilingualism Management in Canada through the Prism of Translation Policies -- tThe Hidden Symbol: The Institutional Discourse of Linguistic Duality in Canada and the Evolving Spirit of the Official Languages Act -- tLanguages in Concert: Linguistic Plurality on Indigenous Land -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCultural and linguistic diversity and plurality are seen as markers of our time, linked to discourses about citizenship and cosmopolitanism in the context of economic globalization in the late twentieth century. It is often monolingualism, however, that informs understanding and policies regulating the relationship between languages, nations, and communities.Grounded by the idea of language as lived experience, Negotiating Linguistic Plurality assumes linguistic plurality to be a continuing human condition and offers a novel transnational and comparative perspective on it. The essays featured cover concepts and praxis in which linguistic plurality surfaces in the public sphere through institutional and individual practices. The collection adopts a critical view of language policies and foregrounds distances and dissonances between policy and language practices by presenting lived experiences of multilingualism. Translation, seen as constitutive to the relations inherent to linguistic plurality, is at the core of the volume. Contributors explore a range of social and institutional aspects of the relationship between translation and linguistic plurality, foregrounding less documented experiences and minoritized practices.Presenting knowledge that spans regions, languages, and territories, Negotiating Linguistic Plurality is a thoughtful consideration of what constitutes language plurality: what its limits are, as well as its possibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLanguage policyzCanada. 0aLanguage policy. 0aMultilingualismxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aMultilingualismxSocial aspects. 0aTranslating and interpretingxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aTranslating and interpretingxSocial aspects. 0aTranslating and interpreting. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Translating & Interpreting.2bisacsh1 aBanerjee, Sanjukta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFettes, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolaron, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuzmán, María Constanza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuzmán, Mar